[0.0,"o","\u001b[39m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38m\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;38;38;38mBuild a Rust CLI tool called crabbymark that renders a markdown file to       \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mGitHub-styled HTML with syntax highlighting and opens it in the default       \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mbrowser. Use clap (derive) for CLI parsing, pulldown-cmark for markdown       \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mparsing (with tables, strikethrough, tasklists, footnotes), and syntect for   \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38msyntax highlighting by intercepting code block events and re-injecting        \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mhighlighted HTML. Use InspiredGitHub theme for light (default) and            \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mbase16-ocean.dark for dark (--dark flag). All CSS should be inline/embedded in\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mthe HTML using GitHub's color palettes. With --pdf, use headless_chrome (with \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mfetch feature) to generate a PDF via print_to_pdf() in the same directory as  \u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\r\n  \u001b[48;2;38;38;38mthe input f"]
